│ `DeadArgumentElimination.cpp`. The pass iterates through all uses of the old function and  │
│ replaces them. When it encounters a `CallInst`, it creates a new `CallInst` with the       │
│ updated function type and arguments.\n\nThe code correctly uses                            │
│ `OldU->replaceAllUsesWith(NewI)` to replace all uses of the old instruction (`OldU`) with  │
│ the new one (`NewI`). However, for a `musttail` call, this is insufficient. The `ret`      │
│ instruction that follows the `musttail` call is a *user* of the basic block, not the call  │
│ instruction itself. Its operand is a `Value*` that points to the call instruction. When    │
│ the old call is deleted, the `ret` instruction's operand becomes invalid.\n\nThe fix is to │
│ explicitly check if the updated instruction was a `musttail` call. If so, we must find the │
│ `ret` instruction that terminates its basic block and update its return value operand to   │
│ point to the newly created call instruction.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe       │
│ required change is to add a special case for `musttail` calls within the use-update loop   │
│ in `DeadArgumentElimination.cpp`. After replacing the old call instruction, we need to     │
│ patch the following `ret` instruction."})                                                  │
