│ instruction within a function whose signature has been changed. Specifically, it's trying  │
│ to use `CreateExtractValue` on a value that is not an aggregate type.                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ This happens because my previous patch, while correctly identifying the need to update the │
│ `ret` instruction following a `musttail` call, did so in a way that created temporarily    │
│ invalid IR. When a `musttail` call that returns a struct is replaced by one that returns a │
│ scalar, my patch updated the `ret` instruction's operand to point to the new               │
│ scalar-returning call. However, the `ret` instruction itself still held the old struct     │
│ type.                                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ Later, when the pass attempts to fix up all `return` instructions in the modified          │
│ function, it encounters this inconsistent `ret` instruction. It sees that the function's   │
│ return type has changed from a struct to a scalar, so it tries to extract the live scalar  │
│ value from the `ret` instruction's operand. But since that operand is now already the      │
│ scalar value (not the original struct-typed value), the `CreateExtractValue` call fails    │
│ with an assertion.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct approach is to perform the `replaceAllUsesWith` *before* manually updating the │
│ `musttail`'s `ret` instruction. `replaceAllUsesWith` will replace all standard uses of the │
│ old call. For a `musttail` call, the `ret` is not considered a standard user, so it will   │
│ be skipped and remain pointing to the old call instruction. After `replaceAllUsesWith` is  │
│ done, we can then safely update the `ret` instruction's operand to point to the new call   │
│ instruction. This ordering avoids creating the invalid intermediate IR that caused the     │
│ crash.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this corrected logic.                                                     │
