│ The previous attempts failed because of an ordering issue. I was trying to fix the `ret`   │
│ instruction associated with a `musttail` call, but this interfered with a later part of    │
│ the same pass that also tries to fix up `ret` instructions. The pass gets confused when it │
│ sees a `ret` instruction that has already been partially updated.                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is that two different parts of `DeadArgumentElimination` are trying to      │
│ "fix" the same `ret` instruction when a `musttail` call's function signature changes.      │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  **Call Site Update:** My patch correctly identifies that when a `musttail` call is     │
│ replaced, the subsequent `ret` instruction must also be updated to refer to the new call   │
│ instruction.                                                                               │
│ 2.  **Function Body Update:** Later, the pass iterates through all `return` instructions   │
│ in the modified function's body to make them conform to the new return type (e.g., by      │
│ extracting values from the old struct-typed return value).                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash happens when the second stage encounters a `ret` instruction that was already    │
│ modified by the first stage. It expects the `ret` to still be returning the old struct     │
│ type, but it's now returning the new scalar type, leading to an assertion failure in       │
│ `CreateExtractValue`.                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct solution is to make the second stage (the function body update) aware of the   │
│ changes made in the first stage. I will add a check at the beginning of the `return`       │
│ instruction update loop. If a `ret` instruction's operand is a `musttail` call, it means   │
│ we have already handled it during the call site update. In this case, we should simply     │
│ `continue` and not process it a second time. This prevents the conflicting modifications   │
│ and resolves the crash.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now implement this fix.                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
