│ This bug stems from the `DeadArgumentElimination` pass's improper handling of `musttail`   │
│ call instructions when modifying function signatures. The pass has two main stages that    │
│ conflict:                                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  **Call Site Update**: When a function's signature changes (e.g., its return type is    │
│ simplified from a struct to a scalar), this stage iterates through all call sites of the   │
│ old function and replaces them with new calls matching the new signature.                  │
│ 2.  **Function Body Update**: After splicing the old function's body into the new one,     │
│ this stage iterates through all `return` instructions within the function and rewrites     │
│ them to conform to the new return type.                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem arises with `musttail` calls. A `musttail` call must be immediately followed   │
│ by a `ret` instruction returning its value. The `ret` is not a standard "user" of the      │
│ call, so `replaceAllUsesWith` does not update it. This requires special handling.          │
│                                                                                            │
│ My previous attempts to add this special handling failed because they created              │
│ inconsistencies between the two stages.                                                    │
│ -   If the call site update stage modifies the `ret` instruction's operand to point to the │
│ new call (which has a new type), the function body update stage later fails. It expects    │
│ the `ret` to have an operand of the *old* type so it can extract the necessary values, but │
│ it finds an operand of the *new* type, causing an assertion.                               │
│ -   If the call site update stage *doesn't* update the `ret`, the IR is temporarily        │
│ invalid, violating the `musttail` contract and causing a verifier failure.                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct solution is to unify the logic. The function body update stage is the correct  │
│ place to handle all `return` instruction modifications. The call site update stage should  │
│ *not* touch the `ret` instruction at all. Instead, we modify the function body update      │
│ stage to correctly handle `ret` instructions that follow a `musttail` call.                │
│                                                                                            │
│ When the function body update stage encounters a `ret` instruction, it checks if the       │
│ returned value comes from a `musttail` call.                                               │
│ -   If it does, it means the call instruction itself has already been replaced with a new  │
│ one (`NewCB`) that has the correct new type. The logic should simply use `NewCB` as the    │
│ new return value.                                                                          │
│ -   If it does not, the existing logic proceeds, building a new return value by extracting │
│ elements from the old `ret`'s operand.                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ This approach ensures that the `ret` instruction is modified only once, in the correct     │
│ stage, using the correct values, thus preserving IR validity and fixing the bug.           │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ @@ -1062,7 +1062,16 @@                                                                     │
│    if (F->getReturnType() != NF->getReturnType())                                          │
│      for (BasicBlock &BB : *NF)                                                            │
│        if (ReturnInst *RI = dyn_cast<ReturnInst>(BB.getTerminator())) {                    │
│ -        IRBuilder<NoFolder> IRB(RI);                                                      │
│ +        // If this is a return from a musttail call, the call has already been            │
│ +        // transformed. We just need to return its result.                                │
│ +        if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(RI->getReturnValue()))                          │
│ +          if (CI->isMustTailCall()) {                                                     │
│ +            auto *NewRet = ReturnInst::Create(F->getContext(), CI, RI);                   │
│ +            NewRet->setDebugLoc(RI->getDebugLoc());                                       │
│ +            RI->eraseFromParent();                                                        │
│ +            continue;                                                                     │
│ +          }                                                                               │
│ +                                                                                          │
│          Value *RetVal = nullptr;                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│          if (!NFTy->getReturnType()->isVoidTy()) {                                         │
│ @@ -1072,6 +1081,7 @@                                                                      │
│            // to return and insert them into our new result.                               │
│            // This does generate messy code, but we'll let it to instcombine to            │
│            // clean that up.                                                               │
│ +          IRBuilder<NoFolder> IRB(RI);                                                    │
│            Value *OldRet = RI->getOperand(0);                                              │
│            // Start out building up our return value from poison                           │
│            RetVal = PoisonValue::get(NRetTy);                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
