│ This bug arises from a complex interaction within the `DeadArgumentElimination` pass when  │
│ it modifies a function containing a `musttail` call. The pass operates in two main stages  │
│ that, in this specific scenario, interfere with each other and produce invalid             │
│ Intermediate Representation (IR).                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  **Call Site Update**: When a function's signature is changed (e.g., its return type is │
│ simplified from a struct to a scalar), this stage finds all call sites of the original     │
│ function. It replaces each old `call` instruction with a new one that adheres to the new   │
│ function signature.                                                                        │
│ 2.  **Function Body Update**: After creating the new function and updating all external    │
│ call sites, the pass splices the body of the old function into the new one. It then        │
│ iterates through all `return` instructions within this body and rewrites them to conform   │
│ to the new return type.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The conflict occurs with `musttail` calls. A `musttail` call must be immediately followed  │
│ by a `ret` instruction that returns its value. The `ret` is not a standard "user" of the   │
│ `call`, so `replaceAllUsesWith` does not update it, necessitating special handling.        │
│                                                                                            │
│ When the call site update stage replaces a `musttail` call inside the function being       │
│ modified, it creates a temporary inconsistency. The new `call` has the updated (e.g.,      │
│ scalar) return type, but it is followed by the original `ret` instruction which still      │
│ expects the old (e.g., struct) value. This violates the `musttail` contract and causes the │
│ verifier to fail before the pass can proceed to the second stage to fix the `ret`.         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct solution is to ensure the `ret` instruction is updated in lockstep with the    │
│ `musttail call` it depends on. This is achieved by modifying the call site update logic.   │
│ When this logic encounters and replaces a `musttail call`, it must immediately also        │
│ replace the subsequent `ret` instruction to correctly return the value from the new call.  │
│ This maintains the `musttail` invariant throughout the transformation.                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The following patch implements this fix by adding special handling for `musttail` calls    │
│ within the call-site update loop, ensuring the `ret` is replaced along with the `call`.    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ @@ -973,6 +973,13 @@                                                                       │
│      if (!CB.use_empty() || CB.isUsedByMetadata()) {                                       │
│        if (NewCB->getType() == CB.getType()) {                                             │
│          // Return type not changed? Just replace users then.                              │
│ +        if (CB.isMustTailCall()) {                                                        │
│ +          // The ret instruction is not a direct user of the call, so we have to          │
│ +          // update it manually.                                                          │
│ +          ReturnInst *RI = cast<ReturnInst>(CB.getParent()->getTerminator());             │
│ +          auto *NewRI = ReturnInst::Create(F->getContext(), NewCB, RI);                   │
│ +          RI->eraseFromParent();                                                          │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│          CB.replaceAllUsesWith(NewCB);                                                     │
│          NewCB->takeName(&CB);                                                             │
│        } else if (NewCB->getType()->isVoidTy()) {                                          │
│ @@ -1018,6 +1025,13 @@                                                                     │
│            }                                                                               │
│          // Now, replace all uses of the old call instruction with the return              │
│          // struct we built                                                                │
│ +        if (CB.isMustTailCall()) {                                                        │
│ +          // The ret instruction is not a direct user of the call, so we have to          │
│ +          // update it manually.                                                          │
│ +          ReturnInst *RI = cast<ReturnInst>(CB.getParent()->getTerminator());             │
│ +          auto *NewRI = ReturnInst::Create(F->getContext(), NewCB, RI);                   │
│ +          RI->eraseFromParent();                                                          │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│          CB.replaceAllUsesWith(RetVal);                                                    │
│          NewCB->takeName(&CB);                                                             │
│        }                                                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
