│ This bug is rooted in the `DeadArgumentElimination` pass's mishandling of `musttail` calls │
│ when a function's signature is modified. The pass has two conflicting stages: one that     │
│ updates call sites and another that updates the function's internal `return` instructions. │
│ When a function containing a `musttail` call is processed, these stages interfere, leading │
│ to invalid Intermediate Representation (IR) and a crash.                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ The core of the problem is that when the pass modifies a function's return type (e.g.,     │
│ from a struct to a scalar), it must update both the call sites and the `return`            │
│ instructions within the function body. For a `musttail` call, the `call` instruction and   │
│ its subsequent `ret` are tightly bound. The call site update logic replaces the `call`,    │
│ but if it doesn't also handle the `ret` instruction, the IR becomes temporarily invalid,   │
│ as a `musttail` call is no longer followed by a `ret` of its value. This causes the        │
│ verifier to fail.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ My previous attempts either failed to update the `ret` atomically, causing a verifier      │
│ error, or updated it in a way that conflicted with the later function body update stage,   │
│ causing an assertion failure.                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct solution is to ensure that the `ret` instruction is updated in lockstep with   │
│ the `musttail` call it depends on. This must be done within the call site update logic.    │
│ When this logic encounters and replaces a `musttail call`, it must immediately also        │
│ replace the subsequent `ret` instruction to correctly return the value from the new call.  │
│                                                                                            │
│ The following patch implements this fix. It adds special handling for `musttail` calls     │
│ within the call-site update loop. When a `musttail` call (`CB`) is replaced with a new one │
│ (`NewCB`), it immediately finds the block's terminating `ret` instruction and replaces it  │
│ with a new `ret` that correctly returns the value of `NewCB`. This is done *before*        │
│ `replaceAllUsesWith` is called, ensuring the IR remains valid and resolving the crash.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp                                  │
│ @@ -973,6 +973,13 @@                                                                       │
│      if (!CB.use_empty() || CB.isUsedByMetadata()) {                                       │
│        if (NewCB->getType() == CB.getType()) {                                             │
│          // Return type not changed? Just replace users then.                              │
│ +        if (CB.isMustTailCall()) {                                                        │
│ +          // The ret instruction is not a direct user of the call, so we have to          │
│ +          // update it manually.                                                          │
│ +          ReturnInst *RI = cast<ReturnInst>(CB.getParent()->getTerminator());             │
│ +          ReturnInst::Create(F->getContext(), NewCB, RI);                                 │
│ +          RI->eraseFromParent();                                                          │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│          CB.replaceAllUsesWith(NewCB);                                                     │
│          NewCB->takeName(&CB);                                                             │
│        } else if (NewCB->getType()->isVoidTy()) {                                          │
│ @@ -1018,6 +1025,13 @@                                                                     │
│            }                                                                               │
│          // Now, replace all uses of the old call instruction with the return              │
│          // struct we built                                                                │
│ +        if (CB.isMustTailCall()) {                                                        │
│ +          // The ret instruction is not a direct user of the call, so we have to          │
│ +          // update it manually.                                                          │
│ +          ReturnInst *RI = cast<ReturnInst>(CB.getParent()->getTerminator());             │
│ +          ReturnInst::Create(F->getContext(), NewCB, RI);                                 │
│ +          RI->eraseFromParent();                                                          │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│          CB.replaceAllUsesWith(RetVal);                                                    │
│          NewCB->takeName(&CB);                                                             │
│        }                                                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
